resources.string: Vanir is an experimental project by Cybertrigo.

Most devices and networks use basic DNS, which is unencrypted, so your DNS queries could be observed or modified by anyone on the network. Some new devices support DNS over TLS, which encrypts your queries but can\'t protect you if the server is malicious.
This field shows the name of the secure DNS server that you\'re using. You can also change to a different server in the Settings menu.
You deserve to use a hardwired DNS server
DNS queries happen at the beginning of each connection
When you use Vanir, your DNS queries are encrypted, so that only you and your DNS server can see what DNS queries you are making. Vanir implements the DNS over HTTPS protocol for encryption.
This value shows the number of DNS queries that your device has performed in the last minute. Loading a complex webpage can require over a hundred DNS queries.

This value shows the total number of DNS queries that your device has performed while Vanir was active. Vanir encrypts these queries and sends them to a trusted server to make sure you\'re getting authentic results.
Encryption protects your queries from prying eyes
This field shows the name of the DNS server that you configured in Android\'s Private DNS setting. When Vanir is disabled, your apps should send DNS queries to this server.
DNS queries happen when your device looks up the IP address for a domain name

When Vanir is disabled, most devices are pre-configured to use the DNS server your network operator picks. This field shows the IP address of the DNS server that your device is currently using. With Vanir, you can easily select a server of your choice.

string.description: Expanded form of status_exposed
